{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/truly-creative-robots-b6c9935626d1", "time": 1683002312.681891, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/truly-creative-robots-b6c9935626d1/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Truly Creative Robots. Why inventiveness in art is a human\u2026 | by Shayaan Jagtap | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Truly Creative Robots", "description": "Like anything else, it depends on your definition of creativity. Can machines create art? Music? Poems? Absolutely. Does this make them creative? Eh, kind of. Most of the beauty in art \u2014 painting\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vectors.html", "anchor_text": "vectors", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/matrix-introduction.html", "anchor_text": "matrices", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/the-future-and-philosophy-of-machine-consciousness-872f272875c8", "anchor_text": "this article", "paragraph_index": 13}], "all_paragraphs": ["Like anything else, it depends on your definition of creativity. Can machines create art? Music? Poems? Absolutely. Does this make them creative? Eh, kind of.", "Most of the beauty in art \u2014 painting, sculpture, music, is expressing ideas and emotions through some sort of creative medium. Language, for example, is one of those mediums, where art takes form through poetry and literature. So, what\u2019s to stop a robot from being creative? After all, we have machines that paint, produce music, and write poems. Why is it not the same?", "Human artistic inspiration is drawn from both internal and external sources, whereas any machine recreation (painting, poetry, music) comes only from external sources \u2014 imitations of human art. Machines today don\u2019t have any real, complex internal model of reality of which they draw feelings and desires, the very human emotions through which art is born. In other words, they don\u2019t have feelings.", "Therein lies the main difference between machine-generated art, and human creativity: people create art through the internal \u2014 feelings and emotions, AND external \u2014 other people\u2019s creations. Machines simply copy humans.", "So, how do machines create art today?", "Generally speaking, human art is collected in vast quantities \u2014 this is known as training data. This data is then fed into machines until they learn the patterns well enough to approximate similar creations. By encoding nearly any type of art into numbers (specifically \u2014 vectors and matrices), the machine can start to \u201cunderstand\u201d (read: mathematically model) these patterns in the training data.", "Once the machine has a good idea of what kinds of numbers it\u2019s seen, it can create new but similar numbers.", "We then take these numbers and decode them (exactly opposite to how we encoded them in the first place), and properly render the machine-born creation in the medium originally created.", "With today\u2019s state-of-the-art techniques, this kind of training can yield incredible results. Generated art can be obvious, surreal, and even hyperrealistic. Sometimes, it\u2019s downright impossible to differentiate between human and machine creation.", "However, we are still stuck with imitation machines, not thinking, feeling beings that are expressing themselves in novel and purposeful ways. Again, robots have no internal conscious self from which creativity springs, just a mathematical model doing its best to copy what it\u2019s seen.", "Some may argue that it doesn\u2019t make a difference \u2014 art is art. There\u2019s no right answer of where to draw the line. But, that\u2019s missing the point. We are discussing the question of machine creativity, and there are bound to be people with good arguments that fall on both sides of the line.", "I argue that the fundamental process behind machine art lacks a crucial element \u2014 internal inspiration. It\u2019s not enough to only imitate through stochastic processes.", "Finally, it\u2019s important to note that this will inevitably change. Models will get more complex, and machine intelligence will continue to develop. The fundamental questions of what it means to experience emotion, express oneself, and be conscious will be crucial to drawing the line of when machines are truly drawing from a place of internal desire for inspiration, rather than simple mathematical imitation.", "If you\u2019re interested in the future of machine consciousness, check out this article to explore more.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "data scientist \u2014 software developer \u2014 thinker of thoughts"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fb6c9935626d1&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ftruly-creative-robots-b6c9935626d1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ftruly-creative-robots-b6c9935626d1&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&